</div><div class=3D"jp-RenderedHTMLCommon jp-RenderedMarkdown jp-MarkdownOu=
tput" data-mime-type=3D"text/markdown">
<p>In this case, we can see that the dataset is heavily imbalanced; the <co=
de>joy</code> and <code>sadness</code> classes appear frequently, whereas <=
code>love</code> and <code>surprise</code> are about 5=E2=80=9310 times rar=
er. There are several ways to deal with imbalanced data, including:</p>
<ul>
<li>Randomly oversample the minority class.</li>
<li>Randomly undersample the majority class.</li>
<li>Gather more labeled data from the underrepresented classes.</li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class=3D"jp-Cell jp-MarkdownCell jp-Notebook-cell">
<div class=3D"jp-Cell-inputWrapper" tabindex=3D"0">
<div class=3D"jp-Collapser jp-InputCollapser jp-Cell-inputCollapser">
</div>
<div class=3D"jp-InputArea jp-Cell-inputArea"><div class=3D"jp-InputPrompt =
jp-InputArea-prompt">
</div><div class=3D"jp-RenderedHTMLCommon jp-RenderedMarkdown jp-MarkdownOu=
tput" data-mime-type=3D"text/markdown">
<p>To keep things simple in this chapter, we'll work with the raw, unbalanc=
ed class frequencies. If you want to learn more about these sampling techni=
ques, we recommend checking out the <a href=3D"https://imbalanced-learn.org=
/stable/">Imbalanced-learn library</a>. Just make sure that you don't apply=
 sampling methods <em>before</em> creating your train/test splits, or you'l=
l get plenty of leakage between them!</p>
<p>Now that we've looked at the classes, let's take a look at the tweets th=
emselves.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
