</div>
<div class=3D"jp-InputArea jp-Cell-inputArea"><div class=3D"jp-InputPrompt =
jp-InputArea-prompt">
</div><div class=3D"jp-RenderedHTMLCommon jp-RenderedMarkdown jp-MarkdownOu=
tput" data-mime-type=3D"text/markdown">
<h3 id=3D"word-tokenization">Word Tokenization<a class=3D"anchor-link" href=
=3D"https://courses.dallard.tech/ml/notebooks/transformers_classification/#=
word-tokenization">=C2=B6</a></h3>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class=3D"jp-Cell jp-MarkdownCell jp-Notebook-cell">
<div class=3D"jp-Cell-inputWrapper" tabindex=3D"0">
<div class=3D"jp-Collapser jp-InputCollapser jp-Cell-inputCollapser">
</div>
<div class=3D"jp-InputArea jp-Cell-inputArea"><div class=3D"jp-InputPrompt =
jp-InputArea-prompt">
</div><div class=3D"jp-RenderedHTMLCommon jp-RenderedMarkdown jp-MarkdownOu=
tput" data-mime-type=3D"text/markdown">
<p>Instead of splitting the text into characters, we can split it into word=
s and map each word to an integer. Using words from the outset enables the =
model to skip the step of learning words from characters, and thereby reduc=
es the complexity of the training process.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class=3D"jp-Cell jp-MarkdownCell jp-Notebook-cell">
<div class=3D"jp-Cell-inputWrapper" tabindex=3D"0">
