</div><div class=3D"jp-RenderedHTMLCommon jp-RenderedMarkdown jp-MarkdownOu=
tput" data-mime-type=3D"text/markdown">
<h2 id=3D"training-a-text-classifier">Training a Text Classifier<a class=3D=
"anchor-link" href=3D"https://courses.dallard.tech/ml/notebooks/transformer=
s_classification/#training-a-text-classifier">=C2=B6</a></h2>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class=3D"jp-Cell jp-MarkdownCell jp-Notebook-cell">
<div class=3D"jp-Cell-inputWrapper" tabindex=3D"0">
<div class=3D"jp-Collapser jp-InputCollapser jp-Cell-inputCollapser">
</div>
<div class=3D"jp-InputArea jp-Cell-inputArea"><div class=3D"jp-InputPrompt =
jp-InputArea-prompt">
</div><div class=3D"jp-RenderedHTMLCommon jp-RenderedMarkdown jp-MarkdownOu=
tput" data-mime-type=3D"text/markdown">
<p>As discussed in &lt;&lt;chapter_introduction&gt;&gt;, models like Distil=
BERT are pretrained to predict masked words in a sequence of text. However,=
 we can't use these language models directly for text classification; we ne=
ed to modify them slightly. To understand what modifications are necessary,=
 let's take a look at the architecture of an encoder-based model like Disti=
lBERT.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class=3D"jp-Cell jp-MarkdownCell jp-Notebook-cell">
<div class=3D"jp-Cell-inputWrapper" tabindex=3D"0">
<div class=3D"jp-Collapser jp-InputCollapser jp-Cell-inputCollapser">
</div>
<div class=3D"jp-InputArea jp-Cell-inputArea"><div class=3D"jp-InputPrompt =
jp-InputArea-prompt">
</div><div class=3D"jp-RenderedHTMLCommon jp-RenderedMarkdown jp-MarkdownOu=
tput" data-mime-type=3D"text/markdown">
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class=3D"jp-Cell jp-MarkdownCell jp-Notebook-cell">
<div class=3D"jp-Cell-inputWrapper" tabindex=3D"0">
<div class=3D"jp-Collapser jp-InputCollapser jp-Cell-inputCollapser">
</div>
<div class=3D"jp-InputArea jp-Cell-inputArea"><div class=3D"jp-InputPrompt =
jp-InputArea-prompt">
</div><div class=3D"jp-RenderedHTMLCommon jp-RenderedMarkdown jp-MarkdownOu=
tput" data-mime-type=3D"text/markdown">
<p>First, the text is tokenized and represented as one-hot vectors called <=
em>token encodings</em>. The size of the tokenizer vocabulary determines th=
e dimension of the token encodings, and it usually consists of 20k=E2=80=93=
200k unique tokens. Next, these token encodings are converted to <em>token =
embeddings</em>, which are vectors living in a lower-dimensional space. The=
 token embeddings are then passed through the encoder block layers to yield=
 a <em>hidden state</em> for each input token. For the pretraining objectiv=
e of language modeling,=E2=81=A0footnote:[In the case of DistilBERT, it's g=
uessing the masked tokens.] each hidden state is fed to a layer that predic=
ts the masked input tokens. For the classification task, we replace the lan=
guage modeling layer with a classification layer.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class=3D"jp-Cell jp-MarkdownCell jp-Notebook-cell">
<div class=3D"jp-Cell-inputWrapper" tabindex=3D"0">
<div class=3D"jp-Collapser jp-InputCollapser jp-Cell-inputCollapser">
</div>
<div class=3D"jp-InputArea jp-Cell-inputArea"><div class=3D"jp-InputPrompt =
jp-InputArea-prompt">
</div><div class=3D"jp-RenderedHTMLCommon jp-RenderedMarkdown jp-MarkdownOu=
tput" data-mime-type=3D"text/markdown">
<blockquote>
<p>note: In practice, PyTorch skips the step of creating one-hot vectors fo=
r token encodings because multiplying a matrix with a one-hot vector is the=
 same as selecting a column from the matrix. This can be done directly by g=
etting the column with the token ID from the matrix. We'll see this in &lt;=
&lt;chapter_anatomy&gt;&gt; when we use the <code>nn.Embedding</code> class=
.</p>
</blockquote>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class=3D"jp-Cell jp-MarkdownCell jp-Notebook-cell">
<div class=3D"jp-Cell-inputWrapper" tabindex=3D"0">
<div class=3D"jp-Collapser jp-InputCollapser jp-Cell-inputCollapser">
</div>
<div class=3D"jp-InputArea jp-Cell-inputArea"><div class=3D"jp-InputPrompt =
jp-InputArea-prompt">
</div><div class=3D"jp-RenderedHTMLCommon jp-RenderedMarkdown jp-MarkdownOu=
tput" data-mime-type=3D"text/markdown">
<p>We have two options to train such a model on our Twitter dataset:</p>
<ul>
<li><em>Feature extraction</em>:: We use the hidden states as features and =
just train a classifier on them, without modifying the pretrained model.</l=
i>
<li><em>Fine-tuning</em>:: We train the whole model end-to-end, which also =
updates the parameters of the pretrained model.</li>
</ul>
<p>In the following sections we explore both options for DistilBERT and exa=
mine their trade-offs.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class=3D"jp-Cell jp-MarkdownCell jp-Notebook-cell">
<div class=3D"jp-Cell-inputWrapper" tabindex=3D"0">
<div class=3D"jp-Collapser jp-InputCollapser jp-Cell-inputCollapser">
</div>
<div class=3D"jp-InputArea jp-Cell-inputArea"><div class=3D"jp-InputPrompt =
jp-InputArea-prompt">
</div><div class=3D"jp-RenderedHTMLCommon jp-RenderedMarkdown jp-MarkdownOu=
tput" data-mime-type=3D"text/markdown">
<h3 id=3D"transformers-as-feature-extractors">Transformers as Feature Extra=
ctors<a class=3D"anchor-link" href=3D"https://courses.dallard.tech/ml/noteb=
ooks/transformers_classification/#transformers-as-feature-extractors">=C2=
=B6</a></h3>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class=3D"jp-Cell jp-MarkdownCell jp-Notebook-cell">
<div class=3D"jp-Cell-inputWrapper" tabindex=3D"0">
<div class=3D"jp-Collapser jp-InputCollapser jp-Cell-inputCollapser">
</div>
<div class=3D"jp-InputArea jp-Cell-inputArea"><div class=3D"jp-InputPrompt =
jp-InputArea-prompt">
</div><div class=3D"jp-RenderedHTMLCommon jp-RenderedMarkdown jp-MarkdownOu=
tput" data-mime-type=3D"text/markdown">
<p>Using a transformer as a feature extractor is fairly simple. We freeze t=
he body's weights during training and use the hidden states as features for=
 the classifier. The advantage of this approach is that we can quickly trai=
n a small or shallow model. Such a model could be a neural classification l=
ayer or a method that does not rely on gradients, such as a random forest. =
This method is especially convenient if GPUs are unavailable, since the hid=
den states only need to be precomputed once.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class=3D"jp-Cell jp-MarkdownCell jp-Notebook-cell">
<div class=3D"jp-Cell-inputWrapper" tabindex=3D"0">
<div class=3D"jp-Collapser jp-InputCollapser jp-Cell-inputCollapser">
</div>
<div class=3D"jp-InputArea jp-Cell-inputArea"><div class=3D"jp-InputPrompt =
jp-InputArea-prompt">
</div><div class=3D"jp-RenderedHTMLCommon jp-RenderedMarkdown jp-MarkdownOu=
tput" data-mime-type=3D"text/markdown">
</div>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class=3D"jp-Cell jp-MarkdownCell jp-Notebook-cell">
<div class=3D"jp-Cell-inputWrapper" tabindex=3D"0">
<div class=3D"jp-Collapser jp-InputCollapser jp-Cell-inputCollapser">
